\intbl\row}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Pain Points & Opportunities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Pain Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fragmented Systems:} Many MDAs develop standalone systems that do not integrate with other government platforms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Duplication of Infrastructure:} Multiple agencies build similar systems without shared platforms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Limited Interoperability:} Data exchange between MDAs is often manual or ad-hoc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Inconsistent Standards:} Some ICT implementations bypass government enterprise architecture frameworks.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Opportunities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Whole-of-Government Interoperability:} Adoption of KeSEL / X-Road architecture for secure data exchange.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Shared Digital Infrastructure:} Government cloud, national data centers, and shared digital platforms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Digital Identity Integration:} Use of Maisha Namba / National Digital ID across government services.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Digital Trust Frameworks:} Use of National PKI and verifiable credentials for digital services.\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 2. TO-BE Process Flowchart (BPMN 2.0)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Future State visualization (Kenya DSAP Architecture \u8211- Whole of Government Digital Platform).}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\pict\pngblip\picw346\pich1462\picwgoal6920\pichgoal29240 }\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 TO_BE Diagram\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Future State Process (TO-BE)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Narrative\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b TO-BE Process: Integrated Digital Government Service Delivery}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The State Department for ICT and the Digital Economy will transition government ICT implementation to a platform-based digital government architecture.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Design Principles:} - {\b Whole-of-Government Architecture:} All ICT projects must comply with Government Enterprise Architecture (GEA) standards before implementation. - {\b Shared Infrastructure:} Digital services are deployed on government cloud and shared platforms, reducing duplication across MDAs. - {\b Secure Data Exchange:} Government systems exchange data through KeSEL / X-Road, ensuring interoperability between authoritative registries. - {\b Digital Trust:} All transactions use National PKI, digital signatures, and secure identity verification. - {\b Citizen-Centric Service Delivery:} Services are published through eCitizen or government digital portals, enabling citizens to access services digitally without visiting physical offices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Optimized Steps (Digital)\par}
